passages.text: 1H25 Review: Sales momentum into 2H25 though SMB margin headwinds persist; Neutral
DDR.AX 12m Price Target: A\\$9.55 Price: A\\$9.25 Upside: 3.2%

GS take: DDR provided a solid 1H25 result, ahead of GSe/VA consensus at the revenue, GP, Pbt and Npat lines, though margins were softer reflecting the mix shift towards lower margin Enterprise deals as growth in the SMB segment remained subdued. FY25 guidance was a key positive at the result, with gross revenue ahead of prior expectations and an implied sequential step up in 2H Pbt margins to support profitability into FY26E. In aggregate, we consider limited scope for near- term earnings outperformance given DDR's significant market position in ANZ and limited evidence of an SMB recovery to date, with current growth factored into the valuation. Maintain Neutral.

Gross revenue was \(\mathsf{A}\S 1,840.5\mathsf{m}\) \(+16\%\) YoY and \(+7\% / + 4\%\) ahead of prior GSe/VA consensus. The strong growth reflects: 1) the shift to higher value enterprise customers, 2) acceleration in revenue from the PC refresh cycle (End point solutions \(+19\%\) YoY), 3) incremental Al revenue including \(\mathsf{A}\S 30\mathsf{m}\) of revenue from large scale Al deployments in Australia, and 4) management commentary that DDR is cycling a softer 1H24.

Gross Profit was \(\mathsf{A}\S 167.1\mathsf{m}\) \(+7\% / + 2\%\) ahead of prior GSe/VA Consensus, though margins declined - 67bps YoY to \(9.1\%\) reflecting the aforementioned mix shift to enterprise customers which are lower margin, as growth in SMB appears to have remained subdued.

Pbt/Npat were \(+5\% / + 4\%\) vs prior GSe, though the Pbt margin was in line at \(3.1\%\) . DDR should also be an immediate net beneficiary of future rate cuts given their variable rate debt profile which would benefit FY25E Pbt margins.
Balance sheet and cash flow. NWC fell to A\\$381m (vs A\\$397

DDR provided FY25 guidance including: 1) FY25 gross revenue of A\(3.7- 3.8bn vs A\)3.75 GSe, supported by high value enterprise deals, PC refresh cycle, as well as incremental upside from additional large Enterprise/ AI deals. DDR noted it does not factor SKB recovery into its guidance, and 2) FY25 Pbt of A\(120- 124m vs A\)122m GSe, reflecting Pbt margin expansion to \(3.4\%\) in 2H25 at the mid point (GSe at \(3.4\%\) ). We expect profitability to strengthen against a softer FY24 baseline and see margin benefits from economies of scale into 2H25.

Valuation: In aggregate we maintain Neutral and increase our price target \(+6\%\) to A\(9.55 (from A\)9.05). Our FY25/26/27E Npat is \(+0\% / - 2\% / + 1\%\) and we roll forward our valuation to a 50/50 FY25/26E blended Ebitda multiple.

DDR is a top 3 distributor of IT hardware and software in ANZ, serving a customer base of \(>8,000\) B2B re- seller partners. DDR's diversified product and vendor portfolio offers protection in the event of a slowdown, although we see DDR as cyclically exposed given \(75\%\) of revenue is from non- recurring hardware sales. That said, DDR's high margins relative to peers, strong balance sheet and tight inventory management place the company in a position to capitalise on market share opportunities as they arise. In addition, DDR's positive working capital cycle offers counter- cyclical cash flow in a potential downturn with the company able to run down inventory to cushion cash flow (as it has done in the past). FY25E represents a tougher environment with softer SMB spending presenting a headwind to margins and earnings growth in the near term. The company has a modest sales growth outlook of mid- single digit FY24- 27E CAGR and appears fairly valued compared to peers and its cash flow generation potential. Hence, we are Neutral- rated on DDR.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
